ions and coarse, limited consumption data. To assess the robustness of our findings, we conduct follow-up experiments replacing the LibriVox consumption proxy with more granular engagement metrics from a proprietary Spotify dataset. These results are an important step towards understanding audiobook narrations and their appeal, offering insights to improve narrator casting and recommendation systems by matching the right voice to the right book, and the right book to the right listener. 2 Related Works 2.1 Computational Paralinguistics and Voice Perception Human voices carry paralinguistic information from which a listener perceives qualities about the speaker’s identity and intention [ neurocomputational_krger_2018 ] . Researchers have developed computational models for paralinguistic tasks such as perceived gender and age classification, health predictors, emotions, social standings, vocal qualities, speaking styles, and even vocal attractiveness (e.g., [ affective_weningerd_2022 , ser_generalisation_goron_2024 , multidimensional_obuchi_2021 , scripted_spontaneous_elisha_2024 , JALALINAJAFABADI2021103018 , spectral_flux_gender , charisma , depression ] ). The classic approach is to train machine learning models on predicted acoustic features from the audio (e.g., pitch, loudness, or spectral) [ schuller2013_computational_paralinguistics ] . Recent works employ sophisticated techniques, such as transformer models, for improved performance at the cost of interpretability [ scripted_spontaneous_elisha_2024 , ser_generalisation_goron_2024 , ethical_awareness_batliner_2023 ] . 2.2 Narration Styles While plenty of audiobook research uses Text to Speech (TTS) and voice conversion (VC) models to deliver expressive speech fit for storytelling (e.g., [ audiobook_tts , sini-etal-2022-investigating ] ), studies indicate that listeners prefer human narrations over synthetic ones [ synthetic_rodero_2021 ] , although some are interested in the ability to customise synthetic narr